  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "5CNQbaDLiCz8iNVUrIM7jufYiS4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "The reactor's SyncManager persists sync state in PGlite (local Postgres-in-WASM) rather than ad-hoc plugin storage. Three tables cover the surface:\n\n| Table | Purpose |\n|-------|---------|\n| `sync_remotes` | Registered remotes with channel_type, push/pull state, failure counts |\n| `sync_cursors` | Per-remote ordinal-based cursor tracking for inbox and outbox |\n| `sync_dead_letters` | Failed operations with error details for retry |\n\nBecause these are durable reactor tables, channel implementations like SwarmChannel don't need their own persistence layer \u2014 cursors survive page reloads and failed ops remain queryable.\n\nThe plugin layer's own `plugin/state.ts` is kept minimal by comparison: it holds only UI-related state (Bee URL, UI cache fields, and drive mapping for the settings panel). This lets the channel evolve without leaking implementation state into the plugin.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:47.000Z"
    }
  },
